<h1>Tutorial 30. Putting Horizontal Ruffles on the Skirt. Part 1.</h1>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I start sewing 11cm ruffles on the central back piece following the highlighted horizontal guidelines. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I put the first ruffle to the very edge of the guideline and stitch over a small section. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I take the second 11cm ruffle, pin its bottom end to the opposite end of the guideline, spread it along the guideline, and mark a sewing start point. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>I finish sewing on the first ruffle stopping at the sewing start point of the second ruffle. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I put down the second ruffle and continue sewing them on simultaneously until the guideline ends. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image020.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image022.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image024.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>I turn the piece on the needle to start the next row of ruffles without interrupting the thread. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image026.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>The first thing I do is put the end of an 11cm ruffle to the end of the guideline and mark its length. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image028.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image030.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Then I put the first 11cm ruffle along the guideline and sew it on down to the marked sewing start point of the second ruffle. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image032.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image034.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I put down the next 11cm ruffle as marked and finish the second horizontal row of ruffles. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image036.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image038.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image040.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I start the third horizontal row of 11cm ruffles. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Again, I turn the piece without taking out the needle or interrupting the thread. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image042.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>I have measured the length of the second 11cm ruffle in the first two rows so I donâ€™t have to put it to the end of the guideline and mark its length again. It is 16cm. </strong>The guideline is 18cm on the pattern but I put the ruffle closer to the edge and it comes out shorter. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image044.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I mark 16cm from the end of the third guideline (3). This is the start point of the second ruffle. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image046.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I mark 16cm (the length of the ruffle) along guidelines (4), (5), (6), and (7). It is important to remember that I need to turn the piece on the needle whenever I move to the next row. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image048.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image050.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image052.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image054.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I return to guideline (3). </strong>I put an 11cm ruffle at the beginning of the row, sew it on down to the start point of the second ruffle, put down the second 11cm ruffle, and continue sewing until the end of the row: first two ruffles simultaneously and then just the remaining part of the second ruffle. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image056.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image058.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image060.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image062.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I turn the piece on the needle and move to row (4). </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image064.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image066.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image068.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image070.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image072.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>And then I turn the piece again and start putting 11cm ruffles along guideline (5). </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image074.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image076.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image078.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image080.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image082.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And I do the same with guideline (6). </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image084.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image086.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image088.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image090.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Finally, I put 11cm ruffles along the last guideline âˆ’ (7). </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image092.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image094.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image096.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image098.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I have made seven horizontal rows of 11cm ruffles. </strong>They hang down creating the effect of sea foam. This effect is achieved thanks to the wavy edges of the ruffles. If the ruffles had smooth edges, they would be plain straight rows of ruffles, which was not what I wanted. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image100.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I remove all thread tails left on the inside of the piece. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image102.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>There are two possible ways to continue: </strong>you can either put 11cm ruffles on all skirt pieces or you can add ruffles of the remaining sizes on the same piece. </p>
<p><strong>I will continue working on the central back piece and put 10.5cm and 10cm ruffles on it before moving to the side pieces. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I highlight the seven guidelines for 10.5cm ruffles with a blue marker. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image104.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Ruffles with a width of 10.5cm are to be put along the guidelines just the same way as 11cm ruffles. </strong>Each row has two of them in it.</p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image106.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image108.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>The higher I move up the piece, the greater is the volume of sewn-on ruffles. </strong>It gets harder and harder to control the guideline and spread the fabric as you sew. In addition, you must keep the ruffles aligned with the guideline. </p>
<p><strong>I want to share with you a simple trick which makes the process of aligning ruffles a lot easier. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Suppose you have attached part of the first ruffle, reached the overlap point, and put down the second ruffle. </strong>The same radius of the inner circle helps you align these ruffles perfectly. I align the edges of the ruffles and pin them together at the end of the first (bottom) row. As the result, it is a lot easier to hold the ruffles in place as you sew. You can see the guideline better and you donâ€™t have to keep trying to catch the end of the second ruffle. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image110.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image112.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image114.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image116.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image118.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I have put all 10.5cm ruffles on the central back piece and now I move to 10cm ruffles. </strong>I will highlight all six guidelines with a marker, mark overlap points, and put two ruffles in each row. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image120.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I switch to the side pieces after putting all ruffles on the central pieces. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I highlight the seven guidelines for 11cm ruffles with a marker. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image122.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>After measuring the guidelines, I noticed that the row lacks 2-3cm even with the smallest possible overlaps. </strong>It would be a real shame having to use a third ruffle or part of it to add these lacking centimeters. It would increase fabric consumption and make the skirt heavier. Please note that I am talking about the lengths of my guidelines: yours may be different. The length of the guideline is 18.5cm on the pattern. The actual length of the row of ruffles is 16cm, which is explained by the fact that I leave 2mm from the edges of the piece and not 5mm as I had previously planned. </p>
<p><strong>There is a simple way to solve the problem: </strong>I stretch every ruffle before sewing it on so as to straighten its inner sewing edge. In this case, two ruffles make a long enough row. Please note that you must sew them on down to the very end of the guideline even if their edges will be covered up by vertical ruffles. I mark overlap points after stretching the ruffles. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%2010/transcripts/Tutorial%2030.files/image124.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<h2> </h2>

